# Logging and Monitoring Rules

References:

- docs/tech-architecture.md
- docs/deployment-guide.md

---

# Purpose

Provide observability for production systems.

Goals:

- Troubleshooting
- Monitoring
- Auditing
- Incident Investigation

---

# Core Principle

If an event is important enough to investigate later,
it must be logged.

---

# Logging Framework

Recommended:

Serilog

---

Providers

Console

File

Database (optional)

---

# Log Levels

Trace

Development only.

---

Debug

Detailed diagnostics.

---

Information

Normal business events.

---

Warning

Unexpected but recoverable.

---

Error

Failed operation.

---

Critical

System instability.

---

# Information Logs

Examples

User Logged In

Affiliate Link Generated

Withdrawal Created

Withdrawal Approved

Webhook Received

Order Approved

---

# Warning Logs

Examples

Invalid Webhook Signature

Failed Login Attempt

Duplicate Webhook

Rate Limit Triggered

---

# Error Logs

Examples

Provider API Failure

Database Failure

Webhook Processing Failure

Job Failure

---

# Critical Logs

Examples

Database Unavailable

JWT Validation Failure Due To Configuration

Application Startup Failure

---

# Structured Logging

Required

Bad

```csharp
logger.LogInformation($"User {userId} created order");
```

---

Good

```csharp
logger.LogInformation(
    "Order created by user {UserId}",
    userId
);
```

---

All logs must be structured.

---

# Sensitive Data Rules

Never log:

- Passwords
- JWT Tokens
- Refresh Tokens
- API Keys
- Access Tokens
- Webhook Secrets
- Full Bank Account Numbers

---

Mask sensitive values.

Example

```text
*****6789
```

---

# Correlation Id

Every request must have:

CorrelationId

---

All logs must include:

CorrelationId

---

Purpose

Trace entire request lifecycle.

---

# Business Event Logging

Must Log

Affiliate

- Link Generated

Orders

- Order Created
- Order Approved
- Order Rejected

Withdrawals

- Request Created
- Approved
- Rejected
- Completed

Admin

- User Suspended
- Settings Changed

---

# Audit Logs vs Application Logs

Audit Logs

Business History

Stored in database.

---

Application Logs

Diagnostics

Stored in logging system.

---

Do not confuse them.

---

# Monitoring Metrics

Track

API

- Request Count
- Error Rate
- Response Time

---

Webhook

- Received Count
- Failed Count
- Duplicate Count

---

Jobs

- Success Count
- Failure Count
- Retry Count

---

Database

- Connection Failures
- Slow Queries

---

# Health Checks

Required

Application

Database

Provider API

---

Endpoint

```text
/health
```

---

Should be machine readable.

---

# Performance Monitoring

Log Slow Requests

Threshold

```text
1000 ms
```

Configurable.

---

Log Slow Queries

Threshold

```text
500 ms
```

Configurable.

---

# Startup Logging

Log

- Application Version
- Environment
- Startup Success

---

Do not log secrets.

---

# Exception Logging

Every unhandled exception:

Must be logged exactly once.

---

Avoid duplicate logging.

---

# Dashboard Integration

Future Metrics

- Daily Orders
- Daily Withdrawals
- Error Rates
- Webhook Success Rate

---

# Retention Rules

Application Logs

30 Days

---

Audit Logs

Never delete automatically.

---

Financial Records

Never delete automatically.

---

